Large Scale Time Series Machine Learning

Ming Ming Zhang

Abstract

We implement stochastic gradient descent in R and apply it to a large scale time series dataset. Moreover, we provide a method for model evaluation which cab be used in the learning curve for time series data.

The data is about the UK government’s land registry. The objective is to predict the housing sale price. Since the purpose of this excecise is for the author’s learning, linear regression is used as the machine learning model. The sliding window time series analysis is used to evaluate the model. As the training size is large, our implemented algorithm stochastic gradient descent will be applied.

Linear regression

Learning curve

Note that the data is time series range from the year 1995 to 2019. First, we randomly select 100 examples in the year 2018 as the cross-validation set. Let \(I = \{1,3,10,30,100,300\}\). Repeat the following process 5 times. For each \(k \in I\), randomly select \(k\) training examples from each year between 1995 and 2017, train linear regression with conjugate gradient, and then compute errors (MSE) on training and cross-validation set using the trained parameter. Lastly, average across errors for each \(k\).

stochastic gradient descent

We will apply the silding window time series analysis to evaluate the model. Since the data has a large training examples for each sliding window, we will use stochastic gradient descent as the optimization function.

k = 5
error_train = rep(0, k)
error_val = rep(0, k)
k = 1

L = list()
for (j in which(names(house)=="Y1995"):which(names(house)=="Y2000")) {
  house_train = house[house[,j] == 1,]
  L[[j-1]] = house_train
}
house_train = L[[1]]
for (i in 2:length(L)) {
  house_train = rbind(house_train, L[[i]])
}
house_train = house_train[,c(1,which(names(house)=="TypeD"):ncol(house))]
house_train = house_train[sample(nrow(house_train)),]
    
XY_train = as.matrix(house_train)
X = XY_train[,-1]
y = XY_train[,1]
  
method = "SGD"
alpha = 1e-7
num_iter1 = 1
num_iter2 = 5e5
(fit = lrLearningSGD(X, y, alpha, num_iter1, num_iter2))

error_train[k] = lrCost(cbind(1,X), y, theta, lambda = 0)[[1]]

By taking the average of errors of sliding windows, the error of linear regression with stochastic gradient descent is

format(mean(error_val), digits = 2)
[1] "3e+11"

Interestly, the error increases as the training window sildes.

ggplot(data.frame(m=1:k, x=error_train, y=error_val), aes(m,x)) +
  geom_line() + geom_line(aes(m,y), color="red") +
  xlab("Number of Sliding Window") + ylab("Error") +
  ggtitle(paste("Linear Regression with SGD", format(mean(error_val), digits = 2)))
